    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Jan 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I beg leave to inform you that the required address, is</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>“A. R. Wallace Esq</p>
<p>Pen-y-Bryn</p>
<p>St. Peters Road</p>
<p>Croydon.”</p> </figure> 
                    <p>Your letter with its unexpected news about the date of the pension has given me much pleasure, for M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Wallace will be able at once to rest from his miscellaneous literary work, &amp; devote all his strength to natural science.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I have the pleasure to remain | Yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. The receipt of all letters has been delayed by snow-drifts</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway</hi> … <hi rend="italic">S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The name of the correspondent is established by the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13033.xml">letter from A. R. Wallace, 29 January 1881</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4935.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Russel Wallace</ref> had been awarded a pension of £200 per year, backdated to July 1879 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12994.xml">letter from A. R. Wallace, 8 January 1881</ref> and n. 3, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13019.xml">letter to G. H. Darwin, 20 January [1881]</ref>). The letter from Seymour, who was Gladstone’s private secretary, has not been found.</note>
        </div>
    
